| **#** | **Technique**             | **When to Use**                              | **Example**                                       | **Pros**                                 | **Cons**                              |
| ----- | ------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| **1** | **Direct Indexing Array** | Values are small integers in a known range   | `freq = [0] * (max_val+1)` → increment `freq[x]`  | 🔹 Fast O(1) access 🔹 Simple            | 🔹 Wastes memory if range is large    |
| **2** | **`collections.Counter`** | Values can be large, sparse, or non-integers | `freq = Counter(arr)`                             | 🔹 Works with any type 🔹 Clean syntax   | 🔹 Slower than list indexing          |
| **3** | **Prefix Sum Frequency**  | Need to query counts in ranges               | Build `prefix[i] = prefix[i-1] + freq[i]`         | 🔹 O(1) range queries                    | 🔹 Requires preprocessing             |
| **4** | **Modulo Buckets**        | Group by remainder or category               | `cnt[x % k] += 1`                                 | 🔹 Ideal for divisibility/group problems | 🔹 Loses info about exact values      |
| **5** | **Difference Array**      | Many range updates before queries            | `diff[l] += 1; diff[r+1] -= 1` → prefix sum later | 🔹 Very fast updates                     | 🔹 Must compute prefix sum at the end |
| **6** | **Boolean Frequency**     | Only need “exists or not” info               | `seen[x] = True`                                  | 🔹 Saves memory 🔹 Fast checks           | 🔹 No actual counts stored            |
| **7** | **Multi-Dimensional**     | Count combinations or grid-based data        | `freq[i][j] += 1`                                 | 🔹 Handles 2D/3D cases                   | 🔹 More complex, more memory          |

